Niels Henrik Abel
\f3\b0  (5 August 1802 \'96 6 April 1829), Norwegian {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematician"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 mathematician}} who made pioneering contributions in a variety of fields. His most famous single result is the first complete proof demonstrating that is impossible to find a general solution for polynomials of degree greater than 4, a problem unsolved for over 250 years. \
He was also an innovator in the field of {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Elliptic_functions"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 elliptic functions}}, discoverer of {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Abelian_function"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 Abelian functions}}, that is, functions that commute with each others. \
Despite his enormous contribution, the majority of his results were carried out during only 6 years of work. Infact, Abel died from Tuberculosis at the age of 26.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \cb3 Regarding Abel, the French mathematician {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Charles_Hermite"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 Charles Hermite}} said: "Abel has left mathematicians enough to keep them busy for five hundred years."\
\
His contribution has been recognised by the institution of the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Abel_Prize"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 Abel Prize}} in mathematics, originally proposed in 1899, to complement the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nobel_Prize"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 Nobel Prizes}}.
